<span class="header1">ANALYSIS/RESEARCH</span>
<p>In this field, employees need to understand how to make money and
how to do business. If you chose to work in this field, you would
study how business is practiced and what companies must do to make
money.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Economist</span><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you enjoy finding clues and drawing
conclusions, you might become an economist. An economist looks at
trends in business and predicts what will happen. For example, you
might study the oil business and decide whether the price of
gasoline will be going up or down. You would probably like this job
if you are naturally curious and enjoy a challenge.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need at least a master's degree for this
job. Many employers will want you to have a Ph.D. Education is very
important.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of economists was $105,020
in May 2019. </blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Market Researcher</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/CH/43326.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Market Researcher" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>A market researcher (or market research analyst) works for a company that makes a product sold to the public. As a researcher, you might work
for a toy manufacturer or a retail store. You would collect
information about what customers want to buy and give your results
to the company.  If you are curious and understand business, this
might be a good job for you.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need a bachelor's degree for this job.
Market researchers start out in entry-level jobs, then they are
promoted to this job.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of market researchers was
$63,790 in May 2019. </blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Computer Systems
Analyst</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/CH/43166.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Computer Systems Analyst" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Computer systems analysts solve computer
problems and use computer technology to meet the needs of an
organization. They may design and develop new computer systems by
choosing and configuring hardware and software. They may also devise
ways to apply existing systems' resources to additional
tasks.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Employers generally prefer applicants who have
at least a bachelor's degree in computer science, information
science, or management information systems. </blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of computer systems
analyists was $90,920 in May 2019. </blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

<span class="header1">NATURE</span>
<p>If you enjoy nature or are concerned about the environment, this
occupational field may be for you.  People who work in this field
enjoy life sciences and understand business.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Life Science Museum
Director</span><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you enjoy helping others know about the
environment and nature, you might become a life science museum
director.  In this job, you would plan and oversee the daily routine
of a museum. You would manage employees and keep the building in
good repair. Most directors start out as a museum curator.  Later,
they are promoted the director's job.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Employment as an archivist, conservator, or
museum director usually requires graduate education and related work
experience. Museum technicians often start work with a bachelor's
degree. </blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of life science museum
directors was $49,850 in May 2019.
</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Zoologist</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/CH/1270.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Zoologist" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Zoologists study the characteristics of animals,
such as their interactions with other species, reproduction,
diseases, and movement patterns.  For example, they might take blood
samples from animals to assess their levels of nutrition.  Most
zoologists work on research teams with other scientists and
technicians.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Zoologists need a bachelor's degree for entry-
level jobs, but a master's degree is often needed for advancement.
A Ph.D is necessary for independant research jobs.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of zoologists was
$63,270 in May 2019. </blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Farmer, Rancher, Agricultural
Manager</span><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Crop farmers and managers determine the best
time to plant seed, apply fertilizer and chemicals, and harvest and
market the crops. Many carefully plan the combination of crops they
grow so that if the price of one crop drops, they will have
sufficient income from another crop to make up the loss. Livestock,
dairy, and poultry farmers and ranchers feed and care for animals
and keep barns, pens, coops, and other farm buildings clean and in
good condition. Although employment on most farms is limited to the
farmer and one or two family workers or hired employees, some large
farms have 100 or more full-time and seasonal workers. </blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Most farmers receive their training on the job,
often by being raised on a farm. However, the completion of a 2-year
associate degree or a 4-year bachelor's degree at a college of
agriculture is becoming increasingly important for farm managers and
for farmers and ranchers who expect to make a living at farming.
</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of farmers/ranchers was
$71,160 in May 2019. </blockquote>

